<h1 class="hero-h">AI for marketing agencies: <em style="color:#00C853;font-style:italic;">the practical guide.</em></h1>
<p class="hero-sub">Marketing agencies are uniquely positioned to benefit from AI — and uniquely at risk if they do not adopt it. Clients are increasingly aware of AI capabilities and expect work that reflects them. Here is the practical guide to deploying AI in a small or mid-sized agency without the common pitfalls.</p>
</div></div>

<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">The agency opportunity</span><h2 class="h2">Why this matters specifically for agencies</h2>
    <p class="body">Agency economics are sensitive to leverage. The same hour of senior time produces dramatically more output with proper AI deployment. That changes the margin calculation on every retainer.</p>
    <p class="body">Properly-deployed agencies are now charging the same retainer fees while producing 2-3x the deliverable volume per engagement. Margins go from 15-25% to 35-50%.</p>
    <p class="body">Agencies that have not adopted are increasingly being out-competed on speed and volume, especially in content-heavy categories.</p>
    </div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">The 5 workflows worth deploying</span><h2 class="h2">Where to start</h2>
    <p class="body"><strong>1. Client brief generation.</strong> From discovery notes to structured creative brief. Reduces brief turnaround from days to hours.</p>
    <p class="body"><strong>2. Content production at scale.</strong> First drafts of blogs, emails, social copy, ad variants. Editorial review by senior creatives.</p>
    <p class="body"><strong>3. Campaign concept variants.</strong> Generate 5-10 concept directions; creative team refines.</p>
    <p class="body"><strong>4. Client reporting and recaps.</strong> Monthly reports, quarterly business reviews, campaign post-mortems. AI handles structure and narrative; account lead reviews.</p>
    <p class="body"><strong>5. Internal account documentation.</strong> Shared Claude Projects per client with brand voice, prior work, account history loaded. New team members onboard 3x faster.</p>
    </div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">Client disclosure question</span><h2 class="h2">The discussion every agency needs to have</h2>
    <p class="body">In 2026, transparent agencies disclose AI use to clients up front. The best framing: "We use AI tools to handle the production work so our senior team can focus more on strategy and quality. All deliverables are reviewed by named senior team members."</p>
    <p class="body">Clients who push back on AI use almost always do so because they assume it means lower quality or higher margin without value transfer. Address both directly in your positioning.</p>
    <p class="body">Agencies that try to hide AI use lose client trust when it comes out (and it always does). Lead with the truth.</p>
    </div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">What never to automate</span><h2 class="h2">The agency-specific lines</h2>
    <p class="body">Strategic recommendations to clients. AI helps frame; senior team owns.</p>
    <p class="body">Brand positioning work. Judgment call that requires deep client context.</p>
    <p class="body">Crisis communication or PR responses. Sensitive enough that AI risk is too high.</p>
    <p class="body">Direct client-facing communication without human review. Even with AI drafts, the email goes from a named person.</p>
    </div></section>

